##INTERNATIONAL STUDENTS IN A DILEMMA: the Day of the flight back to South Korea, the epidemic broke out among onlookers

Micro Signal thelivings

The function introduction, reconstructs our life with the narrative beauty.

The following article is from inSight

Look at this weird and funny world.

Should we turn around and go home? That's the question.

As of midnight on March 14,8,086 new cases of pneumonia had been confirmed in South Korea.

Under the shadow, the path of Chinese students studying in South Korea has become more turbulent than ever.

Shiya was one of those people who got carried away.

March 4 was the 14th day of her return to South Korea. From the confirmed surge in panic to the struggle to get home..

In her isolation diary, she may be able to see what has happened in South Korea these days.

Shiya is located at Seoul's residence

One

The day I flew back to Korea, there was an outbreak

I am a Chinese student in South Korea, currently in Seoul Ewha University Graduate Sophomore.

In early January, I returned home for my winter vacation. On the 20th, when Wuhan notified the whole country of the epidemic, the information related to the new coronavirus pneumonia began to enter my field of vision in a large area.

On the same day, the first case of new coronary pneumonia was confirmed in South Korea.

The confirmed case was a 35-year-old Chinese woman who flew in from Wuhan via Incheon Airport, the News said.

Before the outbreak, I visited the pedestrian mall in my hometown.

When the news came out, I, like most people, began a month-long chinese-style epidemic prevention, during which I stayed at home except for two trips to the supermarket.

Winter in the south is cold and rainy, and the small town where I grew up has never been quieter, although so far there has been no confirmed case in the small town.

More disturbing to me, by contrast, is South Korea's restrictions on the entry of Chinese students.

After the Spring Festival, the outbreak of domestic, Australia, the United States, Japan... more and more countries on China's entry control.

Meanwhile, South Koreans petitioned Blue House for a "total ban on Chinese entry" .

As of March 3,760,000 South Koreans had petitioned Blue House for a "ban on Chinese entry" .

During that time, I kept an eye on immigration policy:

On February 2nd South Korea banned foreigners who had been to Hubei in the past two weeks.

Four days later, the premier added that "necessary measures will also be taken outside of Hubei" . At that time, many South Korean media speculated that the no-entry zone will be expanded.

In the student group, there are people who are constantly being told that their flight has been cancelled.

"Can we go back? "

Such concerns began to creep into our everyday conversations.

A student's flight scheduled for February 24 was canceled. Fearing that she would not be able to leave the country, she rescheduled it for 12 days and became the first among us to return to Korea.

My flight wasn't too badly affected.

On February 15, there were no new confirmed cases in South Korea for five days, and I decided to return to South Korea after five days as planned.

Night view of Dongdaemun before the outbreak

At the time, I never thought the Korean epidemic would get out of control. I'm more worried about the risks of the journey.

On February 20th, at 5 am, I arrived at the Shanghai Hongqiao International Airport.

Before boarding the plane, also specifically confirmed the situation in South Korea: 51 confirmed cases. It's not a problem. In contrast, the number of confirmed cases in Shanghai was even more glaring (334 at the time) .

I took the high-speed train to Shanghai that day. It was the first time I saw such an empty high-speed railway station.

But it's always been there.

During the flight, the stewardess took the temperature of each passenger. The body sounded an alarm as it swept over a young man sitting in the sun by a window

38 degrees. Three.

I was sitting on the back of him, and I screamed, "Damn it! "

Fortunately, after two more tests, his temperature finally returned to normal.

A health status questionnaire filled out on the plane

After a false alarm, I finally arrived at Seoul's Kimpo Airport.

It's a beautiful day we haven't seen in a long time. Just as I was about to report that I was okay, a text message popped up on my phone:

"there have been 82 confirmed cases of coronary pneumonia in South Korea today, bringing the total to 31. "

This increase is almost the total number of confirmed cases in South Korea in the past month. For a second, I felt like my nose was full of germs.

The sudden increase is due to the 31st confirmed case.

According to the news, the 61-year-old South Korean woman, a member of the new World Church in Taegu, has twice rejected doctors'recommendations for nucleic acid tests after showing symptoms.

To make matters worse, before her diagnosis on February 18, she had taken part in two church services with her illness and had been in close contact with thousands of people.

Since then, the confirmed increase in South Korea began to rise sharply, resulting in a "super-transmission event. ".

Since then, the number of people infected in South Korea has exploded. Fighting in South Korea

The immigration process that day was a little different.

After getting off the plane, my fellow passengers and I entered the "Chinese entry passenger only channel" and started taking temperature at the quarantine gate and filling out health status forms.

After that, I joined a new team.

We were asked to install a "self-diagnosis APP" and were tested on the spot to see if the phone we left behind could be dialed.

According to the South Korean authorities, all visitors from China (regardless of nationality) are required to download the "self-diagnosis" APP and fill in their personal physical condition truthfully on a daily basis during the period of home isolation. If you do not report after 2 days, the Korean anti-epidemic authorities will call you, if necessary, the joint police tracking you.

The exit was 15 meters away, and it took half an hour to complete the process.

During Special Times, the school can reimburse the cost of taking a taxi home from the airport. Back at Seoul's House, I hung up my coat and trousers in the laundry room before I dared to set foot inside.

Later, roommates arrived in Seoul.

That night, South Korea confirmed a total of 104 cases of new pneumonia, the first case of infection in the army soldiers, the first death.

Two

South Korean apartheid diary

Visitors from China are required to remain in isolation at home for 14 days.

On my first night back in South Korea, I changed the name of my roommate group to the "yanri-dong Quarantine Point" (I live in Seoul's yanri-dong) , symbolizing the official beginning of segregation.

Isolation at home is no different than the state of the country.

Solving the Three Meals a Day is always the biggest problem.

My roommate was in charge of cooking, so I naturally took on the responsibility of buying food for the whole family. Because you can't go out, you can only buy food online, you order it the day before, you deliver it in the morning.

Open the door and receive the daily order of food online.

But perhaps because of the outbreak, the supply seems to be insufficient, most of the goods are shown as "temporary sold out. ".

I walked around for three more minutes that day, and all the Broccoli in the cart was gone.

On the shopping website, "this week's picks" all said "temporarily sold out. " .

Later, a friend told me that I had to buy food at one or two o'clock in the morning to get what I wanted.

As a kitchen boy, I rely on my roommate's cooking every day.

February 24th is the roommate's birthday. And to celebrate, we ordered takeout.

But the delivery guy wasn't wearing a mask.

To celebrate my roommate's birthday

Not being able to buy a mask is also a problem.

After the outbreak of the disease, the price of face masks in South Korea has skyrocketed.

The KF94, which used to cost about 6 yuan per unit, has risen to 18 yuan, and most are weeks away from delivery.

After several twists and turns, I only from the circle of Friends of the South Korean Daigou there, to 15 yuan per unit price, grabbed 20 have not had time to send out South Korean masks.

Later, some overseas students friends delayed entry because of the epidemic, gave me the mask they had ordered.

In addition to eating and sleeping, I spent most of the day curled up in my 5 sqm cubicle, on my mobile phone, as if I were in a different place in Korea

On the 21st, 204 cases were confirmed, and 48 new cases were mostly related to Xintiandi

On the 22nd, the number of confirmed cases doubled

On the 23rd, the South Korean government raised the alert to the highest "serious" level

On the 24th, people in Taegu lined up for masks for 100 meters

Emergency alarms go off almost daily on cell phones.

Across the screen, it seemed as if the new pneumonia were just heavy numbers, not reality.

The only time I actually saw Seoul was on the last day of February. Remembering that I had not paid my tuition, I had to "risk my life" by going out to the nearest ATM.

At 10 pm, the sky is drizzling with rain, and the pear is much quieter than usual. The shops on the street were still open, but there were only a few passers-by.

If it is the usual, there will be people from the subway entrance, the bus three two or three to get out.

Walk into a lit cosmetics shop, stop at a stall that smells of fish cakes, or pack a hot drink before the shop closes.

At 10:00 p.m. , in front of the deserted pear gate.

There seemed to be an air of unease in the air.

On the first day back, masks were worn far less often on the streets of Seoul than in the country. Now, in the occasional speeding bus, a handful of passengers are wearing masks.

Schools are starting to work from home, too. A daily phone call during the quarantine, which went from a school landline before the 28th to a private number now.

The more tangible fear comes from the Chinese friends around you.

On the second day of my return to Korea, my friend l arrived in Busan. That afternoon, she was informed by the school that a fellow passenger had a fever.

L received a notice from the school

"when I heard the news, I was so shocked that I thought I was going to have a fever, and my ears started to burn. "

The next day, NUCLEIC ACID test results came back for the feverish passenger. Fortunately, it's negative.

She was relieved.

But all the while, she was afraid to tell her parents.

Three

I've seen Korea fight the plague

On the sixth day back in Seoul, South Korea had more than 1,000 confirmed cases.

About 80 per cent of the cases are concentrated in Taegu and North Gyeongsang Province, where Xintiandi is based.

Map of the Korean epidemic. Source: fighting in South Korea

As the number of confirmed cases rose, a series of problems began to surface.

My friend in Taegu says you can't buy a mask in a store, and it takes three weeks to shop online;

In the news, Daegu's bed is starting to run out.

Only 447 of Taegu's 1,017 confirmed cases were admitted to upper-level hospitals on Sunday. As of March 2nd, four patients had died waiting for beds at home..

Online, people began comparing Taegu to "South Korea's Wuhan" .

Fortunately, the South Korean government's measures are relatively positive (at least compared with Japan's) .

First, the Union of local supermarkets, the emergency delivery of more than 2M masks to Taegu. On March 2, South Korea's version of the "shelter" hospital was built.

South Koreans Surf The web, calling for Taegu to shut down its cities.

Seoul is more than 300 kilometers from Taegu, but I still feel Sleeper Cell.

During the period, the most let me above the news is "Seoul, thousands of people rally, the mayor to prevent being spray. ".

Originally, the municipal government in order to prevent the spread of the epidemic, announced the "ban on the Guanghua Gate Square rally. ".

As a result, the next day, Guanghua Gate Square still gathered thousands of people, despite the ban on the rally.

"Moon jae-in step down pan-national struggle headquarters" rally site. Image source MBC

Leading the charge was the Rev. Quan gwang-hoon of the General Council of Churches of Korea, who said at the scene:

"It doesn't matter if we get sick and die. Our purpose is heaven. "

When mayor Seoul arrived and urged them to disperse, the crowd booed and protested.

The good news is that Kwan was arrested on February 25th by a Seoul court. Image Source: MBC

Shouldn't we contain the outbreak first? What if there's a potential patient in the thousands?

These are my worries and my doubts.

"The mayor of Seoul could not be more miserable, " said one member of the student group. "these pigs are teammates. "

More interesting is the online sound of "restricted Chinese entry" .

In fact, Naver had a lot of negative comments about Chinese students long before the outbreak in South Korea.

I read one comment under the headline "Chinese students come to South Korea to worry about the Korean epidemic" :

"If you think this place is dangerous, why are you still in the country? "

A sign forbidding Chinese people from entering a restaurant in Seoul on Feb. 29. Photo courtesy of Associated Press.

Fortunately, the Koreans I met in real life were friendly.

When the outbreak broke out in Wuhan, I also received greetings from the Korean landlord, she told us to take care of epidemic prevention, hope that school, we can safely back to Korea.

And none of my classmates were affected.

Life is normal, but we won't be seeing each other for a while.

Seoul's classmates stayed at home, their cooking enhanced during their isolation.

Four

Should we turn around and go home?

In fact, the biggest problem right in front of us is not "exclusion" at all, but "graduation thesis" .

My friends and I were worried about one thing: finishing school.

March 2nd was supposed to be the first day of school. But under the circumstances, most South Korean universities have postponed their opening day to March 16.

I got a notice from my school that there would be online classes for the first two weeks after school started. But it's the fourth semester, and I don't have any classes. I just have to write my paper.

The professor agreed, instructing me by email for now.

On the 13th day of Quarantine, hoarding still made me feel safe.

Every day, however, the surge of confirmed cases rumbled over me, and it was hard to take my mind off it.

On February 28th a professor at the Seoul National University said the worst case scenario was that 40% of the country's population would be infected and the epidemic would continue until the end of the year.

South Korea has more than 50 million people. 40% is 20 million?

For a moment, I Speechless (TV series) .

Under the outbreak, many international students choose to brake in time. Many of those returning to South Korea are also beginning to think about turning around and heading home.

The return wave from the outbreak sent ticket prices soaring. The most expensive ticket I've ever seen was a flight from Seoul to Shanghai on the 27th, costing more than 26,000 yuan. At present, ticket prices have fallen.

These days, the topic in the group of students, gradually changed from "do not come back" to "do not go back" .

Go Home, rent still pay, academic delay, simply in spending money delay;

And Stay? You never know when things are GONNA get out of hand.

Others calculate a "quarantine charge" : After Han returned from 14 days of isolation, he would be quarantined for another 14 days. If the outbreak in South Korea is brought under control, re-entry would mean a 14-day quarantine.

All told, 42 days of quarantine.

Another, more prodding fact is that returning home is likely to cause more trouble.

In the circle of friends, a classmate was not allowed to enter the community after he returned home.

To tell you the truth, the day after I entered the country, I began to want to go home.

The idea of going home came up more than once.

My friends advised me: "It's too dangerous, do not come back. "

Not only worried about me, some friends also said that the Korean epidemic is so serious, are worried about "Lee Tae won class" can not be more, after all, is filming while broadcasting.

My mother calls me every day to comfort me.

Actually, I was more of a comforter. Once, my mother saw someone wandering in Wuhan after the story shed tears. She began to worry that her daughter would not be able to go home.

It's just, I'm one degree away from graduating. I didn't want to hit the pause button so easily.

Life goes on.

March 5th is the last day of my self-imposed quarantine.

As things stand, however, lifting the quarantine does not mean getting out of the House.

Seoul's head on wind, mixed with the warmth of spring, how much hope it can blow away the remaining years of the epidemic.
